         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>18</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>33</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... not caring about their being separated, wiping away the tears, she says to her husband: Oh lord,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>43ff</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>107, 115</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>23</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>40</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>80</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (It would not be right) for you to go to the forest alone. Therefore, in whichever direction you will go</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>111</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>20</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>33</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(there I will go too). ... in no way will I pay attention to the exertion in the forest, not even ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Not in any way will I care about the hardship in the wilds if I follow you.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>275</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... || In the ?-tune:|| The forests [are] free from evil beings, not by anyone</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>22</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(are its creeks and rivers appreciated) ... as if covered with a carpet of beryl, with lovely spaces of grass</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... If I am together with the children [and] yourself, I will not be worried about... (?)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (even you) will not be annoyed by going to the forest (together with the sons), because ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>20</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... || In the ?.-tune: || When you see the two, adorned with ribbons of flowers,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">If you see the two ornamented with flower strings … you cannot remember kinghood; (if you see) the two childish ones (playing) in the salty bushes … you cannot think about the royal rank and worth. (If you) … the [appropriate] season …, the good and the bad season … if you see the … that cause joys; the courses (?) of the water dug by nature … as if sitting among … you will certainly enjoy yourself. (cf 135a)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>644</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>20</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>25</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [you] will (not) be able to remember [your] kingship. (When you see (?)) the two childish ones (playing) in the salty bushes</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>20</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>32</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... you will not think of [your] (royal) dignity [and] status. 1. When you see the ever changing seasons (?), rains [and] heat (?)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>134</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>21</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the ... which cause longing, (when you) ... in the rivulets of water dug by nature</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1989"/><citedRange>21</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... you will ... like being between ... certainly delight [in]. 2. (The screeching (?)) of the flamingos, peacocks, koels (?) ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">The translation is largely based on <bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>43-44</citedRange></bibl>, and <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/></bibl>.</note><note type="philcomment">The Tocharian version is remarkably close to the Sanskrit text in Āryaśūra's Jātakamālā (cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>51ff</citedRange></bibl>., esp. 57).</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 6.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 8-9.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 12.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">The tune of unknown denomination has 4x25 syllables, rhythm5/5/8/7.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, lines 13 and 15.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 18. The tune mentioned at the beginning of this line has 4x18 syllables, rhythm 7/7/4.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 19.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 21.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment">Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:kern1981"/><citedRange>57</citedRange></bibl>, line 21-25.</note></p>
